.\" termin.al-name: grep
.\" termin.al-usage: grep [-i] [-n] [-r] [-F] [-H|-h] [--] pattern file...
.\" termin.al-summary: Search virtual files with ECMAScript regular expressions.
.TH GREP 1 "" "termin.al" "termin.al Manual"
.ftr B R
.ftr I R
.ftr BI R
.SH NAME
grep \- Search virtual files with ECMAScript regular expressions.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.nf
grep [-i] [-n] [-r] [-F] [-H|-h] [--] pattern file...
.fi
.SH DESCRIPTION
Searches one or more explicit virtual file or directory operands in the order given. Standard input is not supported. A directory operand is rejected unless
.B -r
is present.
.PP
By default,
.I pattern
is compiled by the browser as an ECMAScript regular expression with the
.B u
flag. The
.B -i
option adds the ECMAScript
.B i
flag. Native regular-expression syntax and matching behavior therefore follow the browser running termin.al.
.PP
Options may be clustered. The
.B --
terminator makes every following argument an operand, including a pattern beginning with a hyphen. The
.B -E
option is not supported.
.B -H
and
.B -h
are mutually exclusive.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B -i
Ignore case. Regular expressions use the browser's
.B iu
flags. With
.BR -F ,
the pattern and each logical line are compared after JavaScript lowercase conversion.
.TP
.B -n
Prefix each matching logical line with its one-based line number.
.TP
.B -r
Traverse directory operands recursively in deterministic virtual-filesystem order, subject to the configured entry limit and a maximum depth of 8.
.TP
.B -F
Search for the pattern as a direct literal substring instead of compiling a regular expression. Regular-expression metacharacters have no special meaning.
.TP
.B -H
Always prefix matches with the source filename.
.TP
.B -h
Never prefix matches with the source filename.
.SH REGULAR EXPRESSIONS
The default mode accepts ordinary ECMAScript regular-expression syntax supported by the browser, including groups, alternation, quantifiers, character classes, assertions, escapes and Unicode-aware constructs available with the
.B u
flag.
.PP
If native construction fails, grep rejects the command with the browser's regular-expression diagnostic. grep does not translate the pattern or reinterpret native error positions.
.SH LINES AND OUTPUT
Input is split on newline. A final newline does not create a phantom logical line, an empty file has no logical lines, and carriage return remains part of line content. An empty pattern therefore matches every actual logical line.
.PP
By default, one explicit file omits the filename prefix. Multiple operands or recursive mode include it. Filename comes first, then an optional line number, then the line text. A successful search with no match produces no output.
.PP
At most 1,000 matching lines and 1 MiB of UTF-8 output are emitted. The command stops before an additional line would exceed either bound and reports
.BR runtime.truncated .
Recursive entry truncation is reported separately with the same diagnostic code.
.SH FAILURES AND CANCELLATION
Files are read sequentially. Missing, locked and unavailable operands or descendants are collected in deterministic operand order. If any such failure occurs, the command fails without returning matches from successful operands.
.PP
Cancellation is checked during traversal and reads, between files and logical lines, and before output is returned. One native regular-expression operation is synchronous and is not interrupted after it begins.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
$ grep -n '^Typed' about.md
$ grep -rH 'fixture|typed' projects notes
$ grep -F -- '-literal' about.md
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
help(1), man(1)
